{{Infobox Sailboat Specifications |name = AC75 |image = |imagesize = |alt = |caption = preliminary AC75 concept proposal |class_symbol = |class_image = |class_imagealt = |class_imagesize = |crew = 10-12 <ref>{{cite|url=https://www.americascup.com/en/news/10_THE-ANNOUNCEMENT-OF-THE-PROTOCOL-OF-THE-36TH-AMERICAS-CUP.html|title=The protocol of the 36th America's Cup|publisher=Official AC36 Website|date=2017-09-28}}</ref> |type = [[Sailing hydrofoil|Foiling]] [[Monohull]] |design = |construction = |rig = |keel = |trapeze = |loa = |loh = {{convert|75|ft|m|abbr=on}} |lwl = |beam = |draft = |hull = |mastheight = |mainsailandjib = |sailarea = |mainsail = |jib = |spinnaker = |d-pn = |rya-pn = |phrf = |year = |designer = |location = |role = |updated = |olympic = }} The '''AC75''' ('''America's Cup 75 class''') is a 75-ft [[monohull]] sailboat class, governing the construction and operation of the yachts to be used in the [[2021 America's Cup]]. Conceptual graphics were proposed by the defender on 20 November 2017, and the full Class Rule rule was published on 29 March 2018.<ref group=NB> AC75 Class Rule v1.0 is available at http://cdn.sailingscuttlebutt.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/AC75_Class_Rule.pdf </ref><ref name=AC75v1.0> {{cite book |url= http://cdn.sailingscuttlebutt.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/03/AC75_Class_Rule.pdf |title= AC75 Class Rule v1.0 |authors= Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron; Circolo Della Vela Sicilia; |date= 29 March 2018 |publisher= 36th America's Cup }}</ref>
==Background== Following the [[2017 America's Cup]], where [[Team New Zealand]] defeated ''[[Oracle Team USA]]'', it was decided by the winners that the next [[America's Cup]] competition would be sailed in [[Sailing hydrofoil|foiling]] [[monohull]]s in hope to make the sport more attractive to sailors.
==Specifications== The AC75 has the following maximum specifications. * LOA: 75 ft (23m) * Crew 12 One-design elements of the class have been promised, which might make it easier for new and first-time teams to form for the next America’s Cup and still be competitive. ETNZ is to announce the full class rule details next March but has already indicated that the hydraulics, batteries and control hardware for the foils, for example, could be one-design, with scope for development of control system software.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.yachtingworld.com/americas-cup/111252-111252|title=Radical 75ft flying monohull 'could be fastest America's Cup design ever' - Yachting World|date=2017-11-21|work=Yachting World|access-date=2017-11-25|language=en-US}}</ref>
